{{globalize|date=October 2017}} [[File:Passenger Experience Week 2018, Hamburg (1X7A3702).jpg|thumb|Chair for persons with reduced mobility aboard aircraft]] There are no worldwide uniform standards regulating the provision of '''assistance for airline passengers with disabilities'''. American regulations place the responsibility on the airlines, the European Union's rules make the airport responsible for providing the assistance, whereas in South America there are no regulations at all. The [[International Air Transport Association]] (IATA) is concerned about the difficulties caused by inconsistent regulations.<ref>{{cite web|title=All Passengers This Way {{!}} Airlines International|url=http://airlines.iata.org/analysis/all-passengers-this-way|website=airlines.iata.org|accessdate=12 October 2017}}</ref>
==European Union== According to [[EU]] regulation 1107/2006, [[persons with reduced mobility]] have the right to assistance during airline travel. The assistance is mandated for flights on any airline departing from an airport in the EU or flights to an airport in the EU on an aircraft registered in any EU country.<ref>{{cite web|title=Passengers with disabilities and reduced mobility {{!}} UK Civil Aviation Authority|url=https://www.caa.co.uk/Passengers/PRM/Passengers-with-disabilities-and-reduced-mobility/|website=www.caa.co.uk|accessdate=12 October 2017|language=en}}</ref>
==United States== The [[Air Carrier Access Act]] of 1986 prohibits commercial [[airlines]] from discriminating against passengers with disabilities. The act was passed by the [[U.S. Congress]] in direct response to a narrow interpretation of [[Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act]] of 1973 by the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] in [[U.S. Department of Transportation]] (DOT) v. [[Paralyzed Veterans of America]] (PVA). In PVA, the Supreme Court held that private, commercial air carriers are not liable under Section 504 because they are not "direct recipients" of [[federal funding]] to [[airports]].<ref>{{cite court |litigants=United States Department of Transportation v. Paralyzed Veterans of America |vol=477 |reporter=U.S. |opinion=597 |pinpoint= |court= |date=1986 |url=https://openjurist.org/477/us/597 |accessdate=2017-09-25 |quote=}}</ref>
==IATA ticket codes== Specific [[IATA]] codes are used on the flight ticket to indicate the kind of assistance the person needs, such as wheelchair assistance inside the terminal, between the terminal and the plane, climbing up/down to/from the plane, and moving within the plane.<ref>{{cite web|title=Blind-deaf passengersn (BLND-DEAF)|url=https://www.mobility-service.org/en/blnd-deaf-blind-deaf|accessdate=10 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.londoncityairport.com/intheairport/page/reduced-mobility-and-special-assistance|title=PRM & Special Assistance|publisher=London Airport|accessdate=11 October 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317052401/https://www.londoncityairport.com/intheairport/page/reduced-mobility-and-special-assistance|archivedate=17 March 2015}}</ref> :
{| class="wikitable" |- ! Code !! Meaning |- | WCHR (Wheel Chair Ramp) || Passenger can use stairs but needs a wheelchair or other means of transport for longer distances. |- | WCHS (Wheel Chair Stair) || Passenger cannot use stairs and needs a wheelchair or other means of transport for longer distances. |- | WCHC (Wheel Chair Completely) || Passenger needs a wheelchair. |- | Deaf || Passenger with hearing loss. |- | Blind || Passenger with vision loss. |- | Deaf/Blind || Passenger hearing and vision loss. |- | DPNA || Passenger with developmental or intellectual disability. |}
