'''Hot cycling''' refers to a [[spin class]] performed in a room heated between 80 and 84 degrees Fahrenheit. Like [[hot yoga]], which uses heat to increase an individual's flexibility in the poses. Heated [[exercise]] at temperatures of 100 degrees Fahrenheit has also been shown to strengthen the immune system and increase the volume of [[oxygenated blood]] which can lower cholesterol.<ref>{{cite web|title=Heat acclimation benefits athletic performance in hot and cool conditions|url=https://uonews.uoregon.edu/archive/news-release/2010/10/heat-acclimation-benefits-athletic-performance-hot-and-cool-conditions|website=University of Oregon|publisher=Lorenzo, Santiago, Halliwill, John R., Sawka, Michael N., Minson, Christoper T.|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>
