'''Time-lapse embryo imaging''' is an emerging [[Non-invasive (medical)|non-invasive]] [[embryo selection]] technique used in [[reproductive biology]]. It is used to help select embryos with lower risk of defects and/or greater potential of [[Implantation (human embryo)|implantation.]] The procedure involves taking thousands of pictures of the growing embryo [[in vitro]] during incubation to study [[morphology (biology)|morphology]] and morphokinetic parameters.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Montag | first1 = M. | last2 = Toth | first2 = B. | last3 = Strowitzki | first3 = T. | doi = 10.1016/j.rbmo.2013.05.013 | title = New approaches to embryo selection | journal = Reproductive BioMedicine Online | year = 2013 | pmid =  23933036| pmc = | volume=27 | pages=539–546}}</ref>

There is currently insufficient evidence of a difference in pregnancy rates, live-birth, stillbirth or miscarriage to choose been time-lapse embryo imaging or conventional embryo assessment in [[in-vitro fertilisation|in-vitro fertilisation (IVF)]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Armstrong|first1=S|last2=Arroll|first2=N|last3=Cree|first3=LM|last4=Jordan|first4=V|last5=Farquhar|first5=C|title=Time-lapse systems for embryo incubation and assessment in assisted reproduction.|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|date=27 February 2015|volume=2|pages=CD011320|pmid=25721906|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD011320.pub2}}</ref>{{Update inline|reason=Updated version https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/29800485|date = July 2018}} Further trials are needed in order to determine whether time-lapse embryo imaging can impact on outcomes such as live-birth for couples undergoing IVF or ICSI.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Armstrong|first1=S|last2=Vail|first2=A|last3=Mastenbroek|first3=S|last4=Jordan|first4=V|last5=Farquhar|first5=C|title=Time-lapse in the IVF-lab: how should we assess potential benefit?|journal=Human reproduction (Oxford, England)|date=January 2015|volume=30|issue=1|pages=3–8|pmid=25316446|doi=10.1093/humrep/deu250}}</ref>

